":"`tsid()`"},"168":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-54","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#every-strategy","content":"`bigint`"},"169":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-55","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#every-strategy","content":"See Choosing an ID for the trade-offs, or open a generator reference when you already know which format you need."},"170":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-56","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"UUIDs, ULIDs, TypeIDs, KSUIDs, ObjectIDs, XIDs, and TSIDs have a canonical binary representation. Their `toBytes()` and `fromBytes()` helpers let you store and transport that representation without inventing a second codec."},"171":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-57","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"This matters when an ID lives in a binary database column, a compact protocol payload, or a cache key. A UUID, for instance, is 16 bytes instead of its 36-character string form. The helpers also make the string boundary explicit: convert when data leaves your application, preserve bytes where the system already handles bytes."},"172":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-58","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"String-native formats do not pretend otherwise. Nanoid and CUID v2 have no canonical byte encoding, so they expose a smaller API."},"173":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-59","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#write-into-a-caller-owned-buffer","content":"Binary formats can also write directly into a buffer when an integration already owns the allocation:"},"174":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-60","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#write-into-a-caller-owned-buffer","content":"Public inputs are validated. Explicit random bytes and buffer offsets make tests and boundary integrations deterministic without changing the generator's default monotonic state."},"175":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","type":"page","content":"Choosing an ID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id"},"176":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Choose for the system boundary, not the trend."},"177":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#a-good-default","content":"A good default"},"178":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#time-ordering-is-local","content":"Time ordering is local"},"179":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#time-order-leaks-creation-time","content":"Time order leaks creation time"},"180":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Different identifiers optimize for different constraints. Start with the boundary the value crosses: database index, URL, public API, MongoDB collection, or a native integer column."},"181":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Situation"},"182":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Choose"},"183":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Why"},"184":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Database primary keys"},"185":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"UUID v7 or ULID"},"186":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Time-ordered values improve index locality."},"187":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Public API resources"},"188":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"TypeID"},"189":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"UUID v7 with a readable, domain-specific prefix."},"190":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Short URLs and invite codes"},"191":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Nanoid"},"192":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Compact and URL-safe."},"193":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Values that should resist enumeration"},"194":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"CUID v2"},"195":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Non-sequential, secure identifier."},"196":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"MongoDB `_id` compatibility"},"197":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"ObjectID"},"198":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Matches MongoDB's 12-byte ObjectID format."},"199":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Go rs/xid compatibility"},"200":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"XID"},"201":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Matches rs/xid's compact 12-byte text and binary format."},"202":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Native `BIGINT` storage"},"203":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"TSID"},"204":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"A sortable 64-bit integer, not a UUID-shaped string."},"205":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"Broad standards compatibility"},"206":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"UUID v4"},"207":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","content":"The conventional random UUID format."},"208":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#a-good-default","content":"If you create records in more than one service or need an ID before inserting a row, start with UUID v7. It is a UUID-native value, sort-friendly, and uses a familiar database column type."},"209":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#time-ordering-is-local","content":"UUID v7, ULID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID carry time information. uniku keeps the state required for monotonic sequencing inside one JavaScript isolate; it does not coordinate clocks or sequences between processes or machines."},"210":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id#time-order-leaks-creation-time","content":"UUID v7, ULID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID embed a creation timestamp in the identifier itself. Anyone who can read the ID can decode when the record was created, not just its order relative to other records. That is a feature for index locality and a leak if the ID is public and the creation time is sensitive, for example a document, invoice, or account that should not reveal how old it is. If the identifier is exposed outside your system and creation time must stay private, use UUID v4, CUID v2, or Nanoid instead: none of them encode a timestamp."},"211":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","type":"page","content":"Performance and bundle size","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/performance"},"212":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance","content":"Where uniku beats npm alternatives, where it does not, and what each import weighs."},"213":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"Generation speed"},"214":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/performance#bundle-size","content":"Bundle size"},"215":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/performance#reproduce-these-numbers","content":"Reproduce these numbers"},"216":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance","content":"The numbers below come from the repository's own benchmark and bundle-size tooling, including the rows where an npm alternative wins. Benchmarks run in CI on every push to `main` (GitHub Actions, `ubuntu-latest`), so they reflect ordinary Node.js execution rather than a tuned environment."},"217":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"Each row compares uniku's generator against the npm package it targets: `uuid` for UUID v4/v7, `ulid`, `@paralleldrive/cuid2`, `@owpz/ksuid`, `bson` for ObjectID, `nexid` for XID, `tsid-ts`, `nanoid`, and `typeid-js`."},"218":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"This snapshot comes from the rolling `main` baseline updated on July 14, 2026. Treat the ratios as directional: shared-runner noise and dependency updates can move them. The live baseline is the current source of truth."},"219":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"Generator"},"220":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"uniku vs npm"},"221":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"ULID"},"222":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"116× faster"},"223":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"UUID v7"},"224":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"6.4× faster"},"225":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"CUID2"},"226":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"6.2× faster"},"227":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"TypeID"},"228":{"id":"/docs/guides/performance-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/performance","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/performance#generation-speed","content":"3.2× faster"},"229":{"id":"/docs/g